AGI - Via&nbsp; from the al-Shifa hospital in Gaza: tanks and Israeli army vehicles left the hospital complex where they had entered two weeks ago. According to an Afp journalist, the army shot grenades to cover the withdrawal of heavy vehicles and moved away from the Al-Rimal district to head south-west of Gaza City, to the Tel al-Hawa district. Hamas' Ministry of Health declared that he discovered dozens of bodies in the al-Shifa hospital after the withdrawal of the Idf media. "Decines of bodies of martyrs, some in decomposition state, were found in the complex and around the al-Shifa hospital," announced the ministry in a press release, specifying that material damage is "very significant" on all buildings.&nbsp;
In the meantime, the surgery to which the Israeli Prime Minister was subjected is "reuscised". Benjamin Netanyahu is "in good shape and is beginning to recover", said his office at the end of the operation, followed closely in Israel and abroad.
&nbsp;
The head of the Oms, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, then denounced that yesterday in an Israeli air strike against another hospital in Gaza, that of&nbsp; hospital in Al-Aqsa, four people died and another 17 were wounded. The raid at the hospital was testified by a team of the World Health Organization sent to the place to assess needs and collect incubators for the north of Gaza, said Tedros in a post on X. The Israeli army denied that the hospital was damaged. "A team of the Oms was on humanitarian mission at the Al-Aqsa hospital in Gaza, when a tendopolis inside the hospital complex was struck on Sunday, March 31 by an Israeli air strike," wrote the head of the Oms, who did not provide details about the victims.
&nbsp;
On the other hand, the Israeli army replicated X that one of its aircraft "has hit an operating center of Islamic Jihad and terrorists located in the courtyard of the Al-Aqsa hospital in the Deir al Balah area. "As a result of the impact, the Al-Aqsa hospital building was not damaged and its function was not compromised," he added. Tedros has renewed his appeal for patients, health workers and humanitarian workers to be protected during the conflict and to cease attacks on hospitals. "The ongoing attacks and militarization of hospitals must end - he added -. International humanitarian law must be respected." Tedros urged all parties in conflict to respect the UN Security Council resolution calling for a ceasefire.&nbsp;

