AGI -&nbsp; There are more than 61 million Turkish voters called to the polls for the administrative elections > today throughout the country. The voting operations in the 81 provinces ended shortly ago. In some eastern provinces the seats were closed an hour earlier, after opening an hour ahead of the west of the country, as decided at the Authority for the elections in view of the hours of light in a vast country like the&nbsp;Turkey. Disposal and counting operations will begin immediately>.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Today's is a crucial date especially for President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, decided to reconquer Istanbul, the most populous city of the&nbsp;Turchia&nbsp; lost by his party in the 2019 elections. "It's time to resume work from where it was interrupted, put an end to this period of mud and dirt and put us back at the service of the population as we did for 30 years. The city returned to the problems of 1994, these were 5 years lost," said Erdogan in a rally that took place in Istanbul at the end of the campaign for its candidates. Erdogan in the last and a half months did not lessen energies on an electoral tour in support of the candidates of his party, Akp. The control of his party on Istanbul, a city with a quarter of the country's total population, was the nerve center of Turkish political life. "Who governs Istanbul rules the &nbsp;Turkey," has been one of the favorite mantras of the Turkish leader for years, but has stopped repeating this sentence after the defeat of 2019, suffered by the Republican Party candidate Chp, Ekrem Imamoglu. And it is precisely the challenge between the Chp and the Akp to hold today's day in the balance, also because from the polls it does not seem that the candidate chosen by Erdogan has received a great success. Former Environment Minister Murat Kurum, the President's most loyal and one of the most prominent representatives of the second generation of the party, showed no charism or ability to conquer the public. Born in 1976 in the capital Ankara and father of 3 children, a characteristic appreciated by the Turkish president, he graduated in Construction Engineering. Kurum has climbed positions within the party and from 2018 to June 2023 he served as minister of the environment. It should however be pointed out that Kurum for years has been responsible for building renewal programs in the two largest cities of the &nbsp;Turchia;> programs aimed at replacing old buildings with houses built according to the anti-seism parameters foreseen after the 1999 earthquake. After the earthquake that devastated the south of the country on February 6, 2023, in fact, several scientists warned against the concrete and imminent risk of a sisma of rank greater than 7. Alarms that prompted Erdogan to speed up construction renewal programs and the choice of Kurum should also be understood in this sense. Will it be enough to defeat the mayor in charge Ekrem Imamoglu, > the man who 5 years ago inflicted on Erdogan the most violent battalion of his entire political career? Probably not. It is worth remembering what happened in 2019. After a first round in which Imamoglu imposed himself for a few thousand votes, in a city where the voters are 11.5 million, the Akp filed and returned to the ballot box. A decision badly digested by public opinion, which turned its back on the president's candidate, the little charismatic former prime minister Binali Yildirim and chose Imamoglu, whose victory in repetition was overwhelming (about 800 thousand votes more than the challenger). Imamoglu as 5 years ago is supported by the nationalists of Iyi parties, Kurum by the nationalists of Mhp. However, 5 years ago, Imamoglu's victory was the votes of the Kurds of the HP, but this time they have their own candidate.&nbsp;>
Imamoglu has still led a convincing campaign, it can count on a compact follow-up and charisma that from the stage allows him to establish a direct thread with those who listen to it. A two-and-a-half-year sentence, considered political by the majority of the public, has even strengthened its position with a large part of the population, which saw a political move in the judges' decision. In the last election rounds, the Erdogan party did not achieve the positive results it had achieved in the past in Istanbul.» In short, the game is played in the capital Ankara and in the metropolis on the Bosphorus in a country where the Aegean and Mediterranean coast has always been in the hands of the opposition, but it does not manage to counter the overflow of the Erdogan party in Central Anatolia and on the Black Sea coast. In the cross the east by Kurdish majority, where the favorite is the Kurdish thread party Hdp, insidiated however by the Akp, which saw its consent grow enormously among the Kurds over the years. To see what will happen in the areas affected by the devastating earthquake of 6 February 2023. The party of Erdogan is strong of a overwhelming majority in many of the 11 provinces affected by the earthquake; > a consensus confirmed in the presidential last May, which occurred three months after the earthquake. However important centers such as Antakya and Iskenderun are governed by mayors of the opposition party Chp and ended up in the sight for the management of the sisma. Administrations on which the anathema of Erdogan has also fallen, which has invited the population to vote for their party "to facilitate the reconstruction and recovery post-sym". To make the race in Istanbul even more interesting is the announcement made by Erdogan a few weeks ago, with which he defined his political path at the end. Although in politics everything can happen, according to the current constitution the Turkish leader, who is now 70 years old, would not have the opportunity to run for the presidency in 2028> and the statement of Erdogan leaves room for enormous questions on the future of a Country of 85 million inhabitants, central for the destiny of NATO and Europe. If Kurum wins in Istanbul, those we face will be years when the Akp of Erdogan will further strengthen its position, control over economic policy and society and will aim to prepare the ground for a future signed by Akp. On the contrary, a reconfirm of Imamoglu to the mayor of Istanbul would pave the way for a more pluralistic system, but also for a candidacy to the presidency that would become inevitable at this point. If Imamoglu had to win today in 2028 the race of the presidency would start from a completely different scenario than last year: > This time in fact it would be the President's Akp to have to look for a candidate, while Imamoglu would be the natural leader of the opposition. A scenario that would see the current mayor of Istanbul overwhelmed to lead the country, especially if Erdogan should really follow his own words and withdraw from the political scene.&nbsp;
